Debounce the form value stream with `debounceTime`, drop unchanged snapshots with `distinctUntilChanged`, then use `switchMap` to fire the save — `switchMap` guarantees only the latest snapshot is saved if the user keeps editing during a slow round-trip.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { debounceTime, distinctUntilChanged, switchMap } from "rxjs";

interface Draft {
  id: string;
  text: string;
}

declare function saveDraft$(d: Draft): Observable<{ savedAt: number }>;

export function autoSave(
  draft$: Observable<Draft>
): Observable<{ savedAt: number }> {
  return draft$.pipe(
    debounceTime(750),
    distinctUntilChanged((a, b) => a.text === b.text),
    switchMap((d) => saveDraft$(d))
  );
}
```

The trick is to treat form edits as a hot stream and drop two kinds of noise: rapid keystrokes (use `debounceTime`) and functionally-equal snapshots (use `distinctUntilChanged` with a structural comparator). The final save happens inside `switchMap` so the latest snapshot wins when the user keeps editing mid-flight — an older save that resolves late cannot overwrite newer state.

